Let us consider an example of its application.
Example 2: There are three political parties, P1, P2 and P3. The party P1 has 4
members, P2 has 5 members and P3 has 6 members in an assembly. Suppose we want
to select two persons, both from the same party, to become president and vicepresident. In how many ways can this be done?
Solution: From P1, we can do the task in 4 × 3 = 12 ways, using the multiplication
principle. From P2, it can be done in 5 × 4 = 20 ways. From P3 it can be done in 6 × 5
= 30 ways. So, by the addition principle, the number of ways of doing the task is
12 + 20 + 30 = 62.
