Suppose there are n indistinguishable objects and m indistinguishable containers. Any
distribution is determined purely by an unordered m-tuple of non-negative integers
with sum n. This is equivalent to the number of increasing sequences of length m of
non-negative integers with sum n. But this is precisely the number of partitions of the
integer n with at most m parts, viz., Pn1 + Pn2 + ... + Pnm = Pmn+m , from Theorem 1 of
this unit.
